<HEADLINE> Tour of South China Sea Attracts More Participants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 25 (Xinhua) -- '98 Tour of South China Sea
Cycle Race, which will start on Saturday, has attracted a large
number of articipanting teams, said organizers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cyclists from South African and Australia are participating
for the first time since the race was inaugurated two years ago.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17 teams are entered in the seven-stage event's
first two legs -- a 16-kilometer time trial slated for Saturday in
 Lantau Island, the largest island of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), and a 88 KM criterium at Hong Kong's
former international airport at Kai Tak on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The other stages of the week-long Tour are set for South
China's Guangzhou on Monday, and Zhuhai on Tuesday and
Wednesday. The Tour closes on January 1 after the last two stops
in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Some more teams are to join in the field in Guangzhou to bring
the total number of teams to about 25 for the stage. The
135.6-KM individual road race in Guangzhou is a new stage added
to this year's Tour calendar, which brings the total mileage to
more than 600 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
A liaison group set up for organizing the race, with
representatives from the cycling organizations of China's m
ainland, Hong Kong SAR and Macao, has for the first time included
representatives from Guangzhou and Zhuhai.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Chinese Cycling Association said that the
organizers are considering the initiative from Chinese Taipei to
include a Taipei stage in next year's Tour.
</P>
<P>
Sanctioned by the International Cyclists Union, this year's
Tour had been classified as a Class 2.5 race, with racers'
results to be turned into world ranking points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
