<HEADLINE> Lusaka Talks on Congo (K) Put Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The planned Lusaka summit on
Congo crisis has been rescheduled to ensure maximum participation
as some parties are likely to be absent because of the Christmas
holidays, a Zimbabwean government spokesman said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lusaka talks on the issue of the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) which were set for December 28 have been postponed to early
next year, said presidential spokesman George Charamba.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency reported that the talks, led by
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, were put off till an
unspecified date early next year.
</P>
<P>
A Zambian government spokesman said in Lusaka Friday that the
regional summit on the conflict in the Great Lakes region has
been postponed to next January, without giving the exact date.
</P>
<P>
A peaceful solution to the conflict has eluded Congo (K) many
times after the war to topple Congolese President Laurent Kabila
broke out on August 2 this year.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted by Friday's Herald daily newspaper said
that Southern African Development Community (SADC) leaders could
not agree on whether the rebels should be brought at the same
meeting with Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The source noted that South African President Nelson Mandela
wanted the rebels in Congo (K) to directly participate in the
talks, a position which has been rejected by other leaders. The
source said that it was one of the reasons why the Lusaka meeting
was rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
Kabila has insisted on not negotiating directly with the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zambian President Chiluba, who was supposed to host
the summit, sent his special envoy Eric Silwamba with a message
to Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Silwamba told reporters after his brief meeting with Mugabe
that there was growing confidence that a cease-fire agreement for
the war-torn Congo (K) would be signed soon.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia have deployed troops, air planes
and ammunition to fight with Kabila's troops against the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
