<HEADLINE> Roundup: Election Govt Formed in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala Friday formed an 11-member cabinet designed for
conducting "free, fair and impartial elections" by March/April
1999.
</P>
<P>
The slim cabinet includes the prime minister and 10 ministers,
but it is expected to be expanded later for the inclusion of other
parties wishful to enter in the spirit of an all-party government
for the elections.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached between the Nepali Congress (NC)
and the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism,
CPN-UML), the two major ruling partners, the government shall work
out a detailed plan to ensure the strict adherence by the
government and all political parties to the code of conduct
formulated by the Election Commission to make the elections free,
fair and peaceful.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also called for impartial mobilization of such
sensitive bodies as police, administration and information and
communications for the elections.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML was the strongest advocate of a national government
comprising all parties in parliament for fresh polls when a new
round of political turmoil erupted on December 10 with the
Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) breaking its
three-and-half-a-month alliance with NC.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-ML alleged that the NC had failed to abide by the
agreements reached with it and other left parties in August.
</P>
<P>
On December 11, NC President and Prime Minister Girija Prasad
Koirala recommended to the Royal Palace for dissolution of
parliament for fresh elections on March 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The party also held that given the political situation in the
country, there was no other alternative to holding free, fair and
impartial elections for a fresh popular mandate.
</P>
<P>
The National Democratic Party (RPP) led by former prime
minister Surya Bahadur Thapa echoed, but demanded as well a
substitute government for free and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the NC and the CPN-UML, the two powers in
parliament, agreed on the formation of an all-party government
under Koirala's continued premiership for conducting the
elections.
</P>
<P>
As the CPN-ML, the RPP and other parties registered the same
day a no-confidence motion against the NC minority government,
Koirala resigned Monday under the agreement to pave the way for a
new coalition.
</P>
<P>
He was reappointed as prime minister Wednesday by King Birendra
as he won a majority support in the Lower House of Parliament
backed by the NC, the CPN-UML and the Nepal Sadbhavana Party.
</P>
<P>
The tri-partite government is the sixth in the country since
the mid-term polls in November 1994 which produced a hung
parliament with no single party holding a majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
