<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Youths Urged to Avoid Pre-marital Sex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government
encourages young people to abstain from sex until after marriage
as it is one way to reduce HIV infections in the country, a
cabinet minister said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lands and Agriculture Minister Kumbirai Kangai said the
HIV/AIDS pandemic had adversely affected the most productive age
group in the country, raising concern over the number of talented
lives being lost.
</P>
<P>
The minister was speaking as a guest of honor at the wedding
of a local journalist Kelvin Jakachira in Mutare of east
Zimbabwe, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kangai said the ruling ZANU (PF) had put in place programs to
encourage abstinence until after marriage in an effort to arrest
the spreading of HIV infection and other sexually-transmitted
diseases.
</P>
<P>
He said the programs supported the government's efforts to
curb the spreading of the virus through such organizations as the
national AIDS coordination program.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is only second to Botswana on the world list of
countries worst affected by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
About 1.4 million adult Zimbabweans, 25.8 percent of sexually
active adults between 15 and 49 years are thought to be infected
with HIV. More than 700 people die every week from
HIV/AIDS-related illnesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
