<HEADLINE> Major Political Events in Nepal Since November 1994 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala Friday formed a new tri-partite government for
conducting elections by March/April, 1999. This is the sixth
government in the country since the mid-term polls in November
1994.
</P>
<P>
The following is a chronology of major events in Nepali
politics since November 1994:
</P>
<P>
November 15, 1994 -- The mid-term polls were held and a hung
parliament emerged during which no single party commands a
majority.
</P>
<P>
November 29 -- Man Mohan Adhikari, president of Communist Party
of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML), the largest party in
parliament, formed a one-party minority government.
</P>
<P>
September 10, 1995 -- Adhikari resigned after losing a
no-confidence motion in the Lower House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
September 11 -- Sher Bahadur Deuba from the Nepali Congress
(NC) was named prime minister of a tri-partite coalition.
</P>
<P>
March 6, 1997 -- Deuba resigned after losing a confidence
motion tabled by himself. He had survived two no-confidence
motions before.
</P>
<P>
March 12 -- Lokendra Bahadur Chand from National Democratic
Party (RPP) was sworn in to head a new tri-partite coalition.
</P>
<P>
October 4 -- Chand resigned after losing a no-confidence
motion. RPP President Surya Bahadur Thapa and his supporters also
voted against the government.
</P>
<P>
October 6 -- Surya Bahadur Thapa was appointed prime minister
of another tri-partite coalition.
</P>
<P>
January 8, 1998 -- Thapa recommended to King Birendra for
dissolution of parliament for fresh polls to forestall a
no-confidence motion against him planned by the main opposition
CPN-UML and the faction of RPP led by Lokendra Bahadur Chand.
Later RPP was split into two factions led respectively by Thapa
and Chand.
</P>
<P>
February 4 -- As recommended by the Supreme Court, King
Birendra called a special session of parliament to discuss the
censure motion against Thapa.
</P>
<P>
February 20 -- Thapa survived the censure motion.
</P>
<P>
March 5 -- CPN-UML was split. A faction formed Communist Party
of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML).
</P>
<P>
April 10 -- Thapa resigned to make way for NC to head a new
government under a power-sharing agreement.
</P>
<P>
April 12 -- NC President Girija Prasad Koirala was named prime
minister of a minority government.
</P>
<P>
August 26 -- Koirala reshuffled the cabinet to induct CPN-ML
into the government, turning it into a majority coalition.
</P>
<P>
December 10 -- CPN-ML quit the government, alleging that NC had
failed to implement the agreements reached with it and other left
parties in August.
</P>
<P>
December 11 -- Koirala recommended dissolution of parliament
for fresh polls on March 31, 1999, while CPN-ML and its supporters
called for a special parliament session to discuss their planned
censure motion against the government.
</P>
<P>
December 17 -- King Birendra decided to call a special
parliament session for December 24.
</P>
<P>
December 20 -- NC and CPN-UML agreed to form an all-party
government for conducting elections by March/April, 1999. CPN-ML
led in registering a censure motion against the government.
</P>
<P>
December 21 -- Koirala resigned to make way for the formation
of a new coalition to conduct elections.
</P>
<P>
December 23 -- King Birendra reappointed Koirala prime minister
as he commanded a majority support in the Lower House backed by
NC, CPN-UML and Nepal Sadbhavana Party (NSP).
</P>
<P>
December 24 -- Koirala was administered oath of office by King
Birendra.
</P>
<P>
December 25 -- A tri-partite government comprising NC, CPN-UML
and NSP was formed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
