<HEADLINE> Iraqi Opposition Groups to Set Up Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi opposition groups are
to form an army in southern Iraq to topple the government of
President Saddam Hussein, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
Friday quoted an Iraqi opposition radio as saying.
</P>
<P>
The radio owned by the Iraqi Kurdistan's Islamic Rabeteh
Party, which was monitored in western Iran, reported that 16
Iraqi opposition groups agreed to set up a united armed forces in
their recent meeting in London, attended by a U.S. State Department
senior official.
</P>
<P>
Without giving more details, the report said that
representatives of the Iraqi Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) and
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK), the two biggest groups in the
Iraqi Kurdistan, were present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Following the recent U.S.-British air and missile strikes
against Iraq, Washington has stepped up its efforts to cooperate
with Iraqi opposition groups in order to topple Saddam's
government.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iran-based Supreme Council of the Islamic
Revolution in Iraq (SCIR) stated on Wednesday that it had
never announced readiness to cooperate with the U.S. and Britain
for the Saddam's ouster.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Qatar television reporter in Tehran, the SCIR
chairman Mohammad Baqer Hakim said that every political change
in Iraq should be instituted by the Iraqi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
