<HEADLINE> Arafat, Mubarak to Discuss Mideast Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Palestinian
National Authority Yasser Arafat will arrive here Saturday on a
two-day visit for talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on
the latest development in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Arafat and Mubarak will discuss the future
of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks after Israel suspended the
implementation of the Wye River peace agreement, Palestinian
Ambassador in Cairo Zohdi el Qedra told Egypt's Middle East News
Agency Friday.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said it will not continue to implement the agreement
signed last October on further Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank if the Palestinians do not meet its demands, including the
cancellation of a plan to declare a Palestinian state next May.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel's early parliament elections, expected to be
held between March and June, will put off for months the
implementation of the accord, under which Israel has carried out
the first phase of the troop pullback.
</P>
<P>
The talks are expected to cover the latest U.S.-British
military strikes against Iraq and Yemen's call for an urgent Arab
summit in this regard, said the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain launched a four-day missile
attack on Iraq last Wednesday night in what U.S. claimed as a
retaliation for Baghdad's defiance of the United Nations weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Yemen has called for an Arab summit to discuss the issue. The
Arab League and some of its members, including Egypt, Algeria and
Morocco, have welcomed the proposal. 
</P>
