<HEADLINE> Pak Wants Best Ties With India on Equality Basis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's President Rafiq
Tarar said Saturday that his country is willing to have the best
bilateral and friendly ties with neighboring India on the basis of
equality.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the outgoing Indian High Commissioner Satish Chandra
at the President House, Tarar said, "India should also respond to
the goodwill gesture of Pakistan while accepting the ground
realities."
</P>
<P>
Explaining the ground realities, the president said India must
demonstrate sincerity regarding the resumed process of talks
between the two sides at the foreign-secretary level to address
the outstanding issues with the top issue being Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"The root cause of hostile atmosphere in the subcontinent is
the dispute of Jammu and Kashmir and other outstanding issues
prevailing since 1947," an official source quoted the president as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Tarar noted that the government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif,
during its previous and present tenures, took the initiative to
cool down the temperature between India and Pakistan,
demonstrating willingness to address and identify all the
outstanding issues including Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He, however, charged that India did not demonstrate its
willingness on the subject.
</P>
<P>
Tarar said resolution of the Kashmir issue is not only key to
stability and prosperity in the region but would also result in
the best bilateral and friendly relations between India and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The president hailed the efforts by the departing Indian envoy
and hoped that the coming round of the foreign-secretary level
talks scheduled to be held in New Delhi in February next year
would be encouraging and result-oriented.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the world community to play its due role in
settling the issues of Jammu and Kashmir between the two South
Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
The world community must realize that Pakistan and India are
nuclear powers and tension-free relations between the two
countries could also ensure world peace and stability, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
