<HEADLINE> Miracle Elephant Close to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Round the clock treatment
has been given to a 24-year old elephant in Henan suffering from
acute pancreatitis for the last seven days, but it is reported
that Luweng is now in a critical condition.
</P>
<P>
The female elephant has been lying on the ground since last
Saturday but has already amazed veterinary surgeons, who have been
camped in the elephant compound since the crisis occurred, when
she stood up unaided for more than three hours after almost 80
hours flat-out.
</P>
<P>
The Zhengzhou Zoo in the capital of central China's Henan
Province has already spent 100,000 yuan (about 12,000 US dollars)
in its attempts to save the elephant, which was introduced from
Wuhan Zoo in central China's Hubei Province in 1987.
</P>
<P>
"If she was in the wild, Luweng would die within a few hours
because her heart and lungs would be crushed by her own weight,"
explained one of the vets. "But it is also another miracle that she
has survived so many days, with a pancreas in such a poor state,
as well as problems with other internal organs.
</P>
<P>
According to the vet, tears ran down Luweng's face as her male
friend Babu tried to force his way into the "sickroom" from an
adjoining compound to comfort her.
</P>
<P>
"Many local residents visted the zoo with fruit to see Luweng
and some of them even suggested ways to treat her," said Chen
Xingwang, the zoo keeper.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to spend more money to prolong her life," said
Chen, "but people are already beginning to consider the idea of
having her stuffed after her death and put her on display."
</P>
</TEXT>
