<DOCNO> XIE19981226.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nobel Laureate Calls China Example of Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 26 (Xinhua) -- China is a good example of
how the market could be utilized as a tool for economic
development in a state-controlled economy, Nobel laureate Amartya
Sen said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"China has played the market game with extraordinary skill,"
Sen said at a meet-the-press program at the Press Club in
Calcutta, 1,460 kilometers southeast of here.
</P>
<P>
"They (the Chinese) have shown it is possible for us to make
good use of the market. We have to learn from its achievements,"
said Sen, who returned to his hometown last week after receiving
the Nobel Prize in Economics for the year 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, Sen said, while the market has a contribution in
shaping the world's economic history, it is wrong to depend solely
on market forces for a country's development.
</P>
<P>
Calling for "adequate" government leadership for proper
utilization of the market, the welfare economist said its success
depends on factors like land reforms, education, health care and
protection of backward industries.
</P>
<P>
Non-governmental organizations and the media also have a role
to play in ensuring "proper" utilization of the market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sen said it is very difficult to point out which country in the
world has the best economic policy in terms of human goals.
</P>
<P>
Successful economies in Europe have the problem of growing
unemployment to cope with and the United States has the problems
of inequality in health care, the renowned economist said, adding
that every economy has something to be criticized and learn from.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
