<HEADLINE> Controversial "Learning Revolution" Book Under Fire (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although some who have read the book say there are a number of
good ideas, others declare that it is not suited to traditional
Chinese teaching methods.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Zhenguo, dean of the education department of
Shanghai-based East China Teachers' University, said that it was
not written logically and could not stand close scrutiny. "It
should not be used as a guide book to learning," he insisted.
</P>
<P>
However, the CSC vice-president, Sun Bin, said: "Foreign
authors write differently; they offer the pros and cons through
examples, which is different from the way Chinese authors explain
subjects."
</P>
<P>
Already five million copies have been printed and Sun Bin
agreed that it may seem a lot. "But we intend to create a market
for this book," he said, adding that he confidently expected to
have sold 1.4 million copies by this weekend, since it was first
put on sale.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports from Shanghai reveal that this year Chinese
people have spent more on books than tobacco for the first time
ever. 
