<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Jordan Makes All-out Effort to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has been making an all-out
effort in 1998 to enliven its economy which remained sluggish in
the past years.
</P>
<P>
Want of vitality has been nagging the economy of the kingdom,
which is short of natural resources, especially oil deposit, in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
The GDP (gross domestic products) growth rate, which was 0.8
percent in 1996, slumped to a negative figure in 1997, according
to media reports.
</P>
<P>
An economists-oriented government headed by Prime Minister
Fayez Tarawneh, a U.S.-educated economist, was formed in August.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after sworn in, the cabinet started talks with the
World Bank (WB) and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to
extend their 1989-1999 reform plan for the kingdom for at least
one year.
</P>
<P>
Due to the WB-IMF plan, Jordan has succeeded in stabilizing the
currency rate of the Jordanian dinar and expanding foreign
currency reserves. But it failed to realize healthy GDP growth
rates as expected.
</P>
<P>
The government stepped up privatization process in 1998 in a
bid to add new impetus to the economic activities.
</P>
<P>
It decided in October to sell 49 percent of the shares of the
monopoly Jordan Telecommunication Company to foreign and domestic
investors. The decision was aimed at drawing private investment
and updating the technology and management of the company.
</P>
<P>
Amman invited Western legal and financial advisors in September
to make preparations for the privatization of the national Royal
Jordanian airline.
</P>
<P>
Similar measures were also taken in 1998 to privatize the
Jordan Cement Factories Company, the largest cement producer in
the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
After industry comes trade.
</P>
<P>
Jordan carried on the strong trade ties through 1998 with Iraq,
one of its largest trade partners since the 1991 Gulf War. It
exported 305.3 million U.S. dollars worth of goods to Iraq in 1997
and the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
But its export to other Arab counties, its traditional markets,
stood only at 353 million dollars in the first seven months of
1998, a 22 percent decrease from the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
With the attraction to its traditional markets waning, Jordan
drummed up efforts in 1998 to develop new trade partners.
</P>
<P>
Its exports to eastern Europe and Africa jumped by 255 percent
in the first half of this year over the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
It signed a partnership agreement with the European Union last
year and has been negotiating a trade deal with the European Free
Trade Association this year.
</P>
<P>
The government held rounds of talks this year with Israel and
the Palestinians aimed at breaking Israeli monopoly over the
Palestinian market and facilitating the flow of Jordanian goods
into the area.
</P>
<P>
With the negotiations with the World Trade Organization (WTO)
going on this year, the kingdom holds a high hope of entering the
global trade institution in mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
To encourage import, the government secured 34 million dollars
of credit facilities from the Arab Monetary Fund (AMF) for its
domestic importers.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom tightened restrictions in 1998 on the inflow of
foreign labors to spare more employment opportunities for its own
citizens.
</P>
<P>
The government ordered in September that illegal foreign
workers, who estimatedly make up most of the guest workers
presently in the kingdom, rectify their status and those who
failed to do so would be deported.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government established a special company also in
September to help qualified Jordanians find oversea jobs in order
to get more foreign currency remitted back home.
</P>
<P>
Jordan hopes to shake off economic difficulties and realize a 6
percent GDP growth rate in the year 2000 through wiser policy-
making, industrial renovation, trade extension, development of
human resources as well as foreign financial support.
</P>
<P>
However, with unemployment rate hovering at 27 percent this
year, and in a region haunted by political instability, local
analysts cautioned that more has to be done before the country
could meet its expectations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
