<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Trade Deficit Accounts for 21 PC of Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has a trade deficit of
about 2.03 billion U.S. dollars in 1998, accounting for 21 percent
of its export turnover, Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported
Saturday, quoting the General Department of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's export turnover in 1998 has already reached 9.35
billion dollars or 92 percent of the yearly plan.
</P>
<P>
Its import turnover at the same time is nearly 11.4 billion
dollars or 0.4 percent lower than last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports by domestic enterprises are valued at 7.36 billion
dollars and foreign-invested businesses, nearly 2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Garments and textiles are the country's biggest hard currency
earner with their export turnover reaching 1.35 billion dollars,
up by 0.1 percent over 1997.
</P>
<P>
They are followed by crude oil, which have fetched 1.2 billion
dollars, rice 1.1 billion dollars and footwear 960 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Seafood exports have chalked 850 million dollars, 9 percent
higher than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Other export items like tea, peanuts and assembled computers
and accessories also have seen increases, while cashew nuts, coal,
vegetable and fruits, and handicrafts have registered reductions
in exports. 
</P>
