<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: European Integration Speeds Up in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The year of 1998 has seen the
European Union (EU)'s great efforts to deepen its internal
integration and start its eastward expansion, which demonstrates
the EU's ambition to become a major power in the multi-polar world.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the euro and the eastward enlargement, the EU's
two trans-century tasks, had been written into the 15-nation bloc's
future strategy titled "Agenda 2000" in July, 1997, and achieved
concrete progress this year.
</P>
<P>
In early May, the Council of the European Union, the EU's
policy-making body, set January 1, 1999 as the launching date of
the euro, and announced the list of 11 qualified countries for
membership in the future euro zone.
</P>
<P>
On June 1, the European Central Bank was formally established
to carry out a single monetary policy for the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
On December 3, the euro zone central banks took a coordinated
action to cut interest rates to a level of three percent to
guarantee the smooth launch of the euro. Additionally, the
countries concerned has begun to produce the paper form and coins
of the euro.
</P>
<P>
Currently, with the euro's arrival, the EU could compare in
everything to the United States. The EU said its new currency zone
will cover some 300 million Europeans and will account for 19.4
percent of the world's GDP, compared with 19.6 percent for the
United States
</P>
<P>
The euro will confirm the EU's importance as a commercial power
in the world with an 18.2 percent share of world trade, equal to
that of the United States. Exports from the euro zone have already
been 25 percent higher than those of the United States and twice
those of Japan. The euro is expected to play a growing role in
international trade in the future.
</P>
<P>
The EU also believes that Europe's new currency might soon
change the situation now in which the U.S. dollar plays a dominant
role in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
It is not expected to be a rival to the U.S. dollar, the EU
said, but will complement it, allowing for diversification and
reducing the risk of countries being faced with abnormal currency
fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
The EU commissioner for economic, monetary and financial
affairs, Yves-Thibault de Silguy, has said the single currency is
the crowning achievement of a 40-year process of European
integration. The first benefits will be more economic growth,
more investment, more competitive companies and more jobs for
European citizens.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the long-term strategic goal of European integration
is to realize political union in order to become a very
influential force in the world arena. Therefore, the euro will be
an impetus for the EU to accelerate the process of a politically
unified Europe.
</P>
<P>
The EU's expansion to the central and eastern European
countries is another strategic move which will enable the Western
European bloc to turn into a real European nations' union.
</P>
<P>
Early Last month, the European Commission made the first of its
Regular Reports assessing the progress of the 12 candidate
countries towards EU membership.
</P>
<P>
On November 10, the EU held ministerial meetings for the first
time with Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Slovenia, Estonia
and Cyprus, the six qualified candidate countries for EU
membership, which means the pre-accession negotiations entered
into a substantive stage.
</P>
<P>
But it is hard for the central and eastern European countries
to enter the EU in the near future because of difficulties in
transforming old institutions and structures.
</P>
<P>
For the next enlargement, the EU has given a general picture of
particulars compared with previous enlargements: first, the
development of EU integration requires a higher level of stability
and competitiveness for new members; second, the starting point of
the countries now preparing for membership is very different from
those of previous applicants because of wide differences and huge
economic gaps; third, to keep a future union of over 20 members
operational, it is a must for the EU to reform within the existing
institution.
</P>
<P>
Some experts and analysts here predicted that the earliest date
for EU to adopt the first batch of applying countries will not
come before the year of 2003.
</P>
<P>
Although the euro is expected to spur a higher level of the
integration and the enlargement and enhance the union's muscles,
many problems are still waiting to be solved.
</P>
<P>
The heads of EU members in their recently concluded Vienna
Summit have set the employment strategy as a priority and agreed
to make efforts to lower the unemployment, the social time-bomb,
among other issues.
</P>
<P>
Whether or not the European Union in the future will create a
unified, authoritative voice in international affairs, relies on
its member states give up, in part, their own interests for the
mutual benefit of others, since they are already willing to give
up part of their own monetary sovereignty for a single currency
with a single representative voice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
