<HEADLINE> China Marks Radium Centenary Discovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 26 (Xinhua) -- A century after discovering
radium, which is used in cancer treatment, Nobel Prize winner
Marie Curie is still deeply respected in China for her devotion to
science and to people.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 key Chinese scientists and others involved in
related research attended a commemorative meeting in Beijing today
to mark the discovery of radium by Marie and her husband Pierre
Curie.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Science and Technology Zhu Lilan urged young
Chinese scientists to commit themselves to similar scientific
exploration and to emulate Mrs Curie's courage and patriotism, to
assist the development of their motherland.
</P>
<P>
A recent poll among Chinese women showed that Marie Curie
ranked first among the world's top ten most-respected women.
</P>
<P>
The life story of the Polish-born scientist has been part of
the curriculum for middle school students in China for decades.
</P>
<P>
For her contribution to research into radioactivity, Marie
Curie was awarded the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1903 and the
prize for chemistry in 1911, becoming the first female Nobel Prize
winner and the first scientist to win two Nobel prizes.
</P>
<P>
Scientists attending the meeting loudly praised Marie Curie's
personal strength as she never sought fame or wealth, and gave
herself totally to charity works and helped the poor.
</P>
<P>
"Young students should learn from her strong sense of social
responsibility and noble character," said Zhou Guangzhao, chairman
of the China Association for Science and Technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
