<HEADLINE> Controversial "Learning Revolution" Book Under Fire (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Controversy is raging in
Chinese academic circles and book-shops over the latest edition of
a foreign written book about methods of learning which publishers
hope will sell 10 million copies.
</P>
<P>
As much as 100 million yuan has been earmarked for sales
promotion of the book, "The Learning Revolution", throughout
China, the largest sum ever on a book promotion, but leading
Chinese booksellers are sceptical while top academics are critical
of its style and content.
</P>
<P>
Written by Jeannette Vos from the United States and Gorden
Dryden from New Zealand, the book sold 250,000 copies of its first
edition in China, considered to be a healthy figure, but has come
in for a storm of criticism since its revised edition was launched
on December 12.
</P>
<P>
The two authors put forward bold ideas to reform ways of
learning; believing that how is much more important than what to
learn. They say learning should be interesting and show how it can
be done efficiently.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese company promoting the book said that it believed it
was good and could benefit many people. The Clever Software
(Group) Co. (CSC), the largest education software producer in
China, agreed to spend 100 million yuan (about 12 million
U.S. dollars) to promote "The Learning Revolution".
</P>
<P>
However, Chen Mulin, the manager in charge of book distribution
of the Xinhua Bookstore in Shanghai, the biggest book-chain in
China, said: "We are shocked and dumbstruck by CSC's ambition and
resolution." And he questioned the validity of CSC's target of
selling 10 million copies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
