<DOCNO> XIE19981226.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Governments Blamed for Grave Soil Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Senior Chinese law-maker Buhe
blamed "some local governments and departments" for the country's
still grave situation of soil erosion here today.
</P>
<P>
They are "lax in enforcing the law on water and soil
conservation," and some have been found to deliberately violated
the law for local and departmental interests, he said at the
ongoing meeting of the National People's Congress (NPC) Standing
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee was detailing a
recent environmental survey by the legislature of the middle and
upper reachers of Yangtze and Yellow rivers in October and
November after the ravaged flooding this summer in China.
</P>
<P>
"Soil erosion caused by people is very serious," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the senior law-maker, since the law on water and
soil conservation was enacted seven years ago, erosion control
projects nationwide have benefited 256,000 square kilometers of
areas and money still keeps pouring into the effort.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that the central government allocated 2.1
billion yuan for those projects, maintaining forests and planting
trees.
</P>
<P>
"However," Buhe said, "as our projects cover another 35,000
square kilometers annually, another 10,000 square kilometers of
areas are being eroded."
</P>
<P>
"The total area with serious soil erosion in China amounts to
3.67 million square kilometers, or 38.2 percent of the national
land mass, and with the current rate of recovery, we have to spend
60 to 70 years to make these areas free of soil erosion," Buhe
said.
</P>
<P>
"The upper and middle reaches of the Yangtze and Yellow rivers
are the most important, yet the most difficult places in terms of
water and soil conservation, as well as grasslands encroached by
deserts," he said.
</P>
<P>
He cited several bad examples of violations of environmental
laws. For instance, Shanxi Province have been found to have dump
mines waste to river beds, which poses a major threat to the lives
of people if flooding occurs.
</P>
<P>
He urged a more comprehensive legal framework for the
conservation of water and soil to be set up and local government
officials and departments must know that without sound
environment, economic progress will be like a mansion built on
sand.
</P>
<P>
He said that legislatures at various levels should strengthen
their role in law enforcement supervision and the judiciary must
have those who break the law punished.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
