<HEADLINE> China to Revise Marriage Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The Ninth National People's
Congress (NPC) of China will in its five-year term revise the
country's Marriage Law and formulate several other major laws,
such as laws on administrative permits, fee collection by the
government, according to the ongoing meeting of the NPC Standing
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Law Committee, Civil and Judicial Committee and three
other special committees of the top legislature disclosed the plan
today when reporting their handling of bills submitted by NPC
deputies earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The legislature was told that an special leading group on
revising the marriage law has been set up during the 8th NPC. A
draft revision has been made and is still under discussions and
further revisions by related departments.
</P>
<P>
This law is expected to be included in a legislative plan of
the 9th NPC, a law-maker said.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 NPC deputies have proposed that a unified law
governing administrative procedures be formulated.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Law Committee said that such a legislation has always
been the NPC's top priority because it is crucial to the building
of an honest and clean government, but it is also very difficult,
and they suggest to formulate separate laws in this regard in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
The law on administrative punishment has been passed in 1996,
and the law on administrative appeals is under discussion, and
three other laws, on administrative permit, fee collection and
compulsory measures are also expected to be formulated in five
years, the Law Committee said.
</P>
<P>
The top legislature is also planning to make laws governing the
reform of government restructuring. Other planned laws include
those on civil service, population and family planning and
protecting the rights and interests of farmers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
