<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Evidence to Nanjing Massacre Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Vital evidence which helps
confirm the Nanjing Massacre has been discovered by a historian
in Tianjin who says that it supports the claims of a Japanese
eye-witness whose diary of the events was dismissed by a court in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jikui, former Dean of the History Department of Tianjin
Normal University, revealed yesterday that he has a map which
indicates the existence of three puddles in front of the Nanjing
Higher Court at the time of the 1937 atrocities.
</P>
<P>
Shiro Azuma, a former Japanese soldier, wrote in his war-time
diary that Japanese soldiers poured petrol on and tied hand
grenades to Chinese prisoners who were put into sacks and then
thrown into the puddles in front of the Nanjing court.
</P>
<P>
After publishing his diary in 1996, Shiro Azuma was promptly
sued by a man listed in it as a war criminal. The Tokyo Court
denied the existence of the puddles and therefore ruled against
the accuracy of Shiro Azuma's account.
</P>
<P>
However, Chen's find, which includes a detailed map of
Nanjing published in September 1935, illustrates there were indeed
three puddles in front of the court, covering 2,200, 1,500 and 800
square meters respectively.
</P>
<P>
Chen has now asked that relevant Chinese government departments
advise Shiro Azuma of the find which includes several hand-drawn
maps of Tianjin when it was under the yoke of Japanese military
aggression.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman expressed surprise and
regret over the verdict issued by the Tokyo Court of Japan in the
case of the diary of Shiro Azuma. 
</P>
</TEXT>
