<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Quality Improves in Taihu Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Water quality in Taihu Lake of
east China's Jiangsu Province has improved compared with last
year, announced a monitoring network of the water environment of
the Taihu Lake today.
</P>
<P>
From December 18 to December 20, the network conducted a survey
of the water quality in Taihu Lake, by sampling water both in the
lake and in rivers around the lake.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the area polluted with potassium
permanganate accounted for 71 percent of the lake, while the area
with high phosphorus-content makes up 53 percent of the lake. The
results indicated that the water pollution has reduced compared
with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Taihu lake is one of the three most-polluted lakes in China,
the other two are Dianchi in southwest China's Yunnan Province and
Chaohu Lake in east China's Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the tightened pollution control, about 80
percent of the 1,035 enterprises by the lake which have been
brought under inspection, reached the state requirements for waste
water discharge.
</P>
<P>
On January 1 of 1999, all the units will be restrained from
discharging waste water above the state requirements and the sales
and use of detergent with phosphorus will be completely banned
from the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
