<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Khmer Rouge From 1953 to 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The defection of Khieu
Samphan and Nuon Chea, remaining top Khmer Rouge hard-line
leaders, to the government of Cambodia Friday evening meant the
end of Khmer Rouge's decades of war.
</P>
<P>
The following is a chronology of key events concerning Khmer
Rouge:
</P>
<P>
September 1960: Pol Pot sets up the Communist Party of
Kampuchea.
</P>
<P>
January 1968: Khmer Rouge takes up arms insurrection and starts
a guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
1970: Prince Norodom Sihanouk is toppled; a civil war begins
between Khmer Rouge and the new military government. A U.S.
bombing campaign against North Vietnamese sanctuaries in eastern
Cambodia kills hundreds of thousands of civilians.
</P>
<P>
1975: Khmer Rouge seizes power.
</P>
<P>
1978: Vietnam invades Cambodia to stop Khmer Rouge border
attacks. Phnom Penh falls to Vietnamese two weeks later in January
1979. Khmer Rouge leaders retreat to the Thai border and spend the
next decade fighting against the Hanoi-backed government.
</P>
<P>
October 1991: All Cambodian factions sign the Paris peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
1993: Khmer Rouge boycotts U.N.-supervised general election.
</P>
<P>
July 1994: The government ends negotiations and formally
outlaws Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
August 1996: Phnom Penh announces a major Khmer Rouge split.
Ieng Sary leads thousands guerrillas to defect in Pailin, joining
the government two months later.
</P>
<P>
June 13, 1997: Pol Pot reportedly orders top general Son Sen
and family killed; one week later, former comrades capture Pol
Pot. Ta Mok seizes control of the movement.
</P>
<P>
October 15: Pol Pot speaks to a Western journalist for the
first time in 18 years, telling reporter Nate Thayer that his
"conscience is clear."
</P>
<P>
March 24, 1998: Mass mutiny forces Ta Mok, Khieu Samphan and
Nuon Chea into the jungle and out of Anlong Veng, their stronghold
for eight years.
</P>
<P>
March 31: Several hundred rebels defect at the 10th-centary
Preah Vihear Temple after holding the cultural symbol for five
years.
</P>
<P>
April 15: Pol Pot dies in sleep at 73.
</P>
<P>
May 1: Stepped-up Royal Cambodia Armed Forces (RCAF) offensive
in northern Anlong Veng sends tens of thousands of Khmer Rouge
civilians fleeing over the Thai border.
</P>
<P>
May 12: RCAF claim they destroyed the Khmer Rouge radio on Thai
soil after more than 25 years of broadcasts. The radio has not
broadcast since.
</P>
<P>
June 5: More than 3,000 breakaway Khmer Rouge troops are
integrated into RCAF at Anlong Veng.
</P>
<P>
June 12: Five top Khmer Rouge members defect to government.
</P>
<P>
December 4: The last main Khmer Rouge fighting force surrenders
to the government.
</P>
<P>
December 26: Khmer Rouge remaining top leaders Khieu Samphan
and Nuon Chea surrendered to the government, leaving Cambodia's
guerrilla force with its only military chief Ta Mok. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981226.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
