<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Oil Slide Said Not to Hurt GCC Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The currencies of Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) member states are not likely to be
affected by the sagging oil prices in the world market, the head
of a major foreign exchange in the United Arab Emirates has said.
</P>
<P>
Bashar Al Jallad, president of the Forex, an organization of
foreign exchange and money market dealers, said "although oil
prices have dropped drastically in recent weeks, we do not expect
any threat to GCC currencies," the UAE's Gulf News reported on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Most GCC economies are in good shape with strong currencies,"
Jallad said. He added that the monetary agencies in the GCC
countries have taken measures to ensure their currencies are well
protected.
</P>
<P>
Jallad said the threat to the Saudi national currency riyal was
well handled by the Saudi Arabian Monetary Authority, the currency
has maintained its parity and the momentum will continue.
</P>
<P>
"The Saudi economy is strong and capable of handling any such
crisis," he said. "On the contrary, speculators now will not find
it profitable to speculate in any currency here."
</P>
<P>
According to Jallad, the fixed exchange mechanism with the UAE
currency pegged to the U.S. dollar is "the best at least for the
short term".
</P>
<P>
The fixed exchanged mechanism makes sense not only because oil
is traded in dollars, but also the U.S. economy is the biggest in
the world, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
