<DOCNO> XIE19981226.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Not to Accept Demand for Fissile Moratorium:FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz
said Saturday that Pakistan cannot accept any demand for a
moratorium on the production of fissile materials unilaterally or
multilaterally before the conclusion of a Fissile Material Cut-off
Treaty (FMCT).
</P>
<P>
In response to a question by an Opposition member at the
National Assembly, Aziz said the U.S. and other Western countries
are seeking an early moratorium on the production of fissile
materials under unilateral or multilateral arrangements, pending
the conclusion of FMCT.
</P>
<P>
"Given our genuine security concerns, we cannot agree to any
demand for a moratorium on the production of fissile materials,
unilaterally, or multilaterally, before the conclusion of, or
separately from, a Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan's position on FMCT is based on principles. "We
believe that a fissile material treaty should be instrumental in
promoting both nuclear non-proliferation and nuclear disarmament,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
A fissile material treaty aimed at only preventing further
proliferation of nuclear weapons would be discriminatory and thus
ineffective, said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Aziz noted that Islamabad's another major concern is the
unequal stockpiles of fissile materials existing at the global,
regional and sub-regional levels.
</P>
<P>
"When the substantive negotiation starts on FMCT in Geneva next
year, Pakistan will pursue its position which is shared by a
majority of the non-aligned countries represented in the
Conference of Disarmament," Aziz added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
