<HEADLINE> Israeli Allied Militiaman Killed in S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 26 (Xinhua) -- An official of the Israeli
allied South Lebanon Army (SLA) was killed Saturday by
unidentified gunmen in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Ghasan Daher, 32, a SLA's local security official, was shot
dead by a group of gunmen at his home in Shabba village inside the
Israeli occupied security zone in south Lebanon, the Voice of the
People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The assassins escaped after the shooting, which has raised to
34 the number of SLA militiamen killed in south Lebanon since the
start of this year, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, SLA blocked all ways linked to the
rest of the village and launched a house-to-house search for
the murderers.
</P>
<P>
The killing of SLA official came at a time when the conflicts
are escalating between Israeli forces and the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah guerrillas who are leading a war trying to oust Israeli
forces and its proxy SLA out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north
from cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, eight Lebanese guerrillas, including a mother
and her six children, were killed in Israeli air raids on the
country's eastern Bekaa Valley.
</P>
<P>
The next day, Hezbollah slammed scores of Katyusha rockets
into northern Israel in retaliation, wounding 16 Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The new wave of casualties Israeli forces suffered has once
again forced the Israeli government into reconsidering its policy
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu will chair a
cabinet meeting on Sunday to address a final way out for
his forces from the quagmire in the border enclave. 
</P>
</TEXT>
