<HEADLINE> Manila Wants to Strike Peace With Rebels in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said on Saturday that his administration wants to conclude
peace talks in 1999 with Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) and
National Democratic Front (NDF) rebels.
</P>
<P>
In a weekly radio interview, Estrada said: "We have to go ahead
on the peace process initiated by the past administration."
</P>
<P>
"We have to continue that because former President Fidel Ramos
was quite successful in negotiating with such rebel groups as the
MNLF (Moro National Liberation Front) and the AFP (Armed Forces of
the Philippines) Movement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he has retained retired General Manuel Yan and
retired General Alexander Aguirre as the government's chief
negotiators with the rebel groups "so we will succeed in attaining
genuine peace."
</P>
<P>
The two retired generals served as chief government negotiators
during the Ramos administration, which kicked off its peace talks
with the NDF in 1993 and the MILF in 1996. But the negotiations
with the two groups stalled amid differences over certain issues.
</P>
<P>
The government's talks with the MILF have remained at the
committee levels as the rebel group insists on establishing a
separate Islamic republic in the south.
</P>
<P>
The government's talks with the NDF also hit a snag because the
group wants to implement a human right pact it earlier forged with
the government in accordance with their own constitution. 
</P>
