<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Capital's Population Grows by 79% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Population in Maputo, capital
of Mozambique, had grown to about 970,000 by August 1997 census,
427,100 more, or 79 percent more over the figure in 1980, when
the country conducted its first census.
</P>
<P>
The National Statistics Institute of Mozambique made the
announcement to the city parliament members Friday, the paper
Noticias reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The statistics institute said the population growth rate of
Maputo, the biggest city of this southern African country, was
3.4 percent during the period between the two censuses, almost
doubling the national average rate which was 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
During this period of time, the natural population growth
rate, or the birth rate minus mortality rate, stood at 2.8
percent, and the immigration from the countryside contributed to
the other 0.6 percent growth rate of the capital city's
population increase.
</P>
<P>
The second census showed that 40 percent of the city's
population were under 15, with an average age of 18.4, which
means that over half of the population were under 18.4 years of
age, and the above-65 age group took less than two percent.
</P>
<P>
The latest census indicates that the country had 16.5 million
people by August 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
