<HEADLINE> Zambia Holds up Imported Sorghum for Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has confiscated 7,000
tons of sorghum from Care International company which allegedly
contravened the Plant and Diseases Act when importing the grains,
Zambia Daily Mail reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This came to light Thursday when Southern Province Deputy
Minister Elias Miyanda inspected the sheds stocking maize and
sorghum pending distribution to various parts of the province.
</P>
<P>
The grain was seized by the Ministry of Agriculture, Food and
Fisheries, suspecting it to contain fungi and other pest
diseases. But the report did not say where the sorghum came from.
</P>
<P>
If the phytosanitary examination in Mount Makulu Research
Station confirms the grain has problems, the sorghum would be
destroyed or dumped.
</P>
<P>
About 258,000 tons of wheat from the United States has also
been impounded in Chirundu bordering Zimbabwe, 200 kilometers
southeast of Lusaka earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The wheat was suspected to be infested with Karnal Bunty, a
disease commonly found in America. 
</P>
