<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Constitution Review Act Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi has signed the Constitution of Kenya Review Commission
(Amendment) Act, making it law.
</P>
<P>
The Act, signed by Moi in central Kenyan town of Nakuru
Thursday, is to be published immediately after the Christmas
holidays and before the new year, national press reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The act was passed by parliament on December 8 with only minor
amendments. It seeks to set up a three-tier system to review the
constitution -- namely, the Commission, the National Consultative
Forum and District Forum.
</P>
<P>
The most fundamental changes in the composition of the
25-person Commission is the inclusion of one pastoralist and at
least one person with a physical disability as commissioners.
</P>
<P>
The nomination of commissioners by political parties, civil
society, and special interest groups must be done within 15 days
from the date of the Act's commencement, which should be no later
than 30 days after its publication.
</P>
<P>
Political parties have 13 seats on the commission while the
Women's Political Caucus -- a grouping of about 43 women's
organizations -- have five.
</P>
<P>
At least eight seats must be preserved for women and at least
two commissioners must come from each of the country's eight
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Collecting and collating citizens' views on constitution will
take 13 months, preparing a report and a draft bill will take
another six months while dissemination and a debate of report and
draft bill will take three months.
</P>
<P>
"The commission must not only collate and collect the views...
but must also accurately reflect those views in their
recommendations and draft bill (on constitution amending)," said
Attorney-General Amos Wako in a statement issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
If everything works to schedule, a new constitution should be
in place by mid-2001, one year to the next general elections,
Wako said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981226.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Output Value of Different Industrial Sectors in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 26 (Xinhua) -- China's state sector accounted
for less than half of the gross industrial output value in
October, according to the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The output value of state owned and state owned holding
enterprises reached 234.57 billion yuan in October and that of
collectively owned enterprises, a component of the public assets,
amounted to 148.64 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The output value that came from foreign investment and
investment made by Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan was 129.84 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
That of enterprises with other ownership stood at 24.83 billion
yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
