<HEADLINE> China's Output of Timber Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 26 (Xinhua) -- China's output of timber in
the first ten months this year dropped by 1.8 percent against the
same 1997 period, according to the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the output of timber in October was 1.7
million cubic meters and that of the January-October period
amounted to 25.38 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The production of saw wood in turn dropped by 4.5 percent on a
year-on-year basis, with an output of 3.55 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Many experts have put the blame on excessive logging of trees
along the flooding rivers for this summer's devastating flooding.
</P>
<P>
The government has imposed bans on irrational lumbering in
many forest areas, particularly those on the upper reaches of the
rivers in a bid to curb soil erosion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
