<HEADLINE> More Bulgarians Visit Theaters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Over 1.1 million Bulgarians, or
one in every eight people in this country, have visited
state-owned theaters in the outgoing year, up 10-15 percent from
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
As shown by official statistics released on Saturday, about 50
state-owned theaters across this East European country have put
up a total 5,720 shows in 1997 and earned an equivalent of some
700,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Sofia Film Director Aleksander Donev was quoted
by a Bulgarian Telegraph Agency report as saying, the number of
movie goers went up some 10 percent in the past year despite the
hike of ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
The upside, Donev said, is that the number of middle-aged
movie goers has been on the rise, as teenager types of films,
action films and those showing beatings and chases are less
popular during the last year and a half.
</P>
<P>
Blockbuster box office successes in Bulgaria were Titanic and
Armageddon, both from the United States, in 1998, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that tickets should not become more
expensive before more comfortable conditions, as well as audio
and video technologies, are provided in movie theaters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
