<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Hit Heavily by Oil Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 26 (Xinhua) - Tanzania has lost
billions of Tanzania shillings in revenue from rampant smuggling
of petroleum products and tax evasion since last year's El Nino
rains, local newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Officials of major oil companies, quoted by the media, said
that the temporary disruption of communication systems by the El
Nino rains and the suspension of the major oil companies'
services initiated the petroleum smuggling from neighboring
Kenya, Malawi and other states.
</P>
<P>
Managers of BP Tanzania Limited, Agip Tanzania Limited,
Tanzania Service Station Limited, TOTAL and GAPCO said that major
oil companies in Tanzania are suffering an estimated 30 percent
loss of business due to the smuggling.
</P>
<P>
They said in the local market like in Mwanza and Kilimanjaro
regions, unscrupulous businessmen sell petrol at 400 shillings
and diesel at 330 shillings per liter while the official prices
are fixed at 420 shillings and 380 shillings per liter
respectively (1 U.S. Dollar equals to some Tanzania shillings).
</P>
<P>
"The smugglers naturally charge less because they do not pay
taxes to the government as is done by the major oil companies,"
one manager said.
</P>
<P>
Major oil dealing companies have called on the government to
take immediate and stern measures to stabilize the country's
troubled petroleum industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
