<HEADLINE> Tanzania Invites Bids for Printing IDs Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has restarted
the process of inviting bids for printing its national Identity
Cards (IDs) after canceling the tender to a British company.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen companies from different parts of the world have
applied for printing the cards, a project with an estimated cost
of 150 million U.S. Dollars, "The African" reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of the state-owned Central Tender Board N. Nkinga
said here Friday that a total of 33 companies have purchased the
documents for the tender but the majority of them prove to be
unqualified. However, he declined to name the companies, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The successful bidder will print IDs for all Tanzanians
residing in the country and abroad, foreign missionaries and
their dependents living in Tanzania, foreign students studying in
the country and refugees.
</P>
<P>
A British company Regional Services Limited which had won the
previous tender to print some 20 million cards, has filed a suit
with the High Court challenging the cancellation by the Tanzanian
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The tender won by the British company was canceled on claims
that the bidding process was lack of transparency, sources said.
</P>
