<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Difficult Year for Zimbabwe's Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 26 (Xinhua) -- 1998 saw Zimbabwwe face a
difficult year with many challenges to its economy.
</P>
<P>
Low economic growth rate, high inflation and interest rates,
unstable exchange rate, poor export performance and social unrest
experienced this year, had a negative impact on the country's
overall economic performance.
</P>
<P>
The southern African country adjusted this year's economic
growth rate to less than 2.4 percent from an earlier forecast of
3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector, the first major pillar of the
country's economy, is expected to grow merely by 3.2 percent this
year with most crops registering reduced yields because the El
Nino related bad weather forced farmers to reduce their sown
areas.
</P>
<P>
Maize, the Zimbabwean's staple food grain, is estimated to
yield 1.4 million tons this year, a decrease of 19.5 percent as
against that of last year, compelling the country to import about
500,000 tons from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco, the country's biggest foreign currency earner,
contributes 25 percent to Zimbabwe's total foreign currency
earnings. Although the country harvested a generally better
quality crop of 210 million kilograms, a 7.7 percent increase
over last year, its earnings declined to just a little over 300
million U.S. Dollars from last year's near 400 million Dollars,
because tobacco prices have slumped by half this year.
</P>
<P>
In the manufacturing sector, Zimbabwe's second major economic
mainstay, big state-owned firms made huge losses and many
companies were forced to close down, though the sector was
projected to grow by 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The mining sector performed poorly since the beginning of
economic reforms in 1991 and prospects for improvement next year
are bleak due to depressed prices and rising production costs.
</P>
<P>
Inflation continued to be a major problem for Zimbabwe. The
average inflation rate for 1997 was 18.9 percent. It raised to 34
percent in November this year. The country's inflationary
tendencies are much greater than its regional and international
trading partners, rendering its exports less-competitive.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean Dollar continued to fall since 1997 and the
exchange rate has plummeted from 16 Zimbabwean Dollars against
one U.S. Dollar at the beginning of this year to 36 against one
U.S. Dollar at present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981226.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Difficult Year for Zimbabwe's Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zimbabwe's stock market, Africa's second largest one, has also
been hard hit resulting in a decline in market capitalization of
45 percent over the past year. The industrial index declined by
41.6 percent while the mining index dropped by 57.7 percent in
late September this year.
</P>
<P>
This year's budget deficit reportedly will be about 7.4
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Unemployment rate of 50 percent and the 45 percent interest
rate also constituted major challenges to the country. High
unemployment rate has been described as "a time bomb" and high
interest rate forced quite a number of factories and mines to
collapse.
</P>
<P>
Observers here held that poor macro-economic performance came
from three factors:
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the southeast Asian financial crisis has had severe
adverse effect on Zimbabwe's economy. Some Asian countries have
withdrawn their orders of importing Zimbabwe's tobacco and
mineral products. This year's export is projected at nine percent
below last year's level.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, poor rains during the past two years and low mineral
prices on the world market have eroded the country's two main
sources of income, thus affecting business and the livelihood of
the people.
</P>
<P>
Over 60 percent of the Zimbabwean people now live in poverty,
causing social unrest. Strikes, demonstrations and riots against
the government took place one after another this year, and
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, Zimbabwe's involvement in the war of the Democratic
Republic of Congo further deteriorated the country's economy.
Zimbabwe sent more than 6,000 troops to support Congolese
president Laurent Kabila to fight the rebels who want to topple
the Kabila government. Zimbabwe's opposition parties and the
trade unions demanded that the government publish the expenditure
in the war along with figures of injuries and deaths.
</P>
<P>
When the 1999 new year is coming, the Zimbabweans are
gratified that the government, business sectors and the labor
movement have agreed to hold a tripartite meeting to seek ways of
improving the deteriorating economy.
</P>
<P>
In his state of the nation address to parliament on December
23, President Robert Mugabe noted that 1998 has been a difficult
year which presented many challenges both to the government and
the general populace. However, he said, "My government is
convinced that the future holds better prospects for the nation."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
