<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Studies Possible Impact of Euro on Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is studying the
possible impact of euro, the single European currency to be
introduced by the European Union at the beginning next year, on
its economy.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Bank, the central bank, has formed a five-member
committee to examine the possible impact of the new money on the
country's external trade, press reports said Saturday, quoting
bank officials.
</P>
<P>
Banks, both local and foreign, would be allowed transactions in
the new European currency upon recommendations by the committee
comprising bankers and private sector representatives, they said.
</P>
<P>
"We have nothing to hurry," Bangladesh Bank Governor Dr
Mohammad Farashuddin said.
</P>
<P>
About 45 percent of Bangladesh' exports go to the European
Union countries, but taka, the Bangladeshi currency, is pegged to
the U.S. dollar and the banks operating in the country would not
immediately ask to handle transactions in the new currency, the
governor said.
</P>
<P>
The euro would be available for business transactions from next
January and the currency notes are coming only after three years
from 2000. "It will give us the necessary time to adjust," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The effective exchange rate in Bangladesh is determined on the
basis of the currency basket, according to Farashuddin.
</P>
<P>
After the study, the central bank is expected to issue a
circular permitting banks to open euro accounts for transactions
related to exports, imports and remittances, and only then, the
banks could accept euro deposits in the country and determine
rates of exchange, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
