<HEADLINE> Thai Armed Forces Face Big Cut in Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's armed forces may
get only about half of their combined spending budget of more than
112 billion baht (3.1 billion U.S. dollars) proposed for the next
fiscal year, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai has said.
</P>
<P>
Chuan, also defense minister, informed the Defense Council of
the prospect of a hefty cut in their proposed budget during a
two-hour meeting last week, Saturday's Bangkok Post reported.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said the chance for new purchase of weapons would remain
open provided they were really needed for national security.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite hefty cuts the defense budget for fiscal
2000 would still be higher than for the current fiscal year ending
next September.
</P>
<P>
Chuan promised to try to convince the cabinet to allow the
armed forces to have more than half of their proposed budget of
112.881 baht (3.14 billion dollars), of which 60 percent has been
earmarked for salaries, 30 percent for repayment of debts incurred
from arms purchases, and the remaining 10 percent for purchases of
new equipment.
</P>
<P>
Military sources said much of the budget would be spent on
small ammunition which had not been purchased by the armed forces
over the past two years. 
</P>
