<HEADLINE> Paralysis Victims Reach 71 in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The number of people struck
by paralysis has increased to 71 in the past two days in three
villages of Banke district, mid-western Nepal, The Kathmandu Post
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily said that in the period, the number
of cases in Zhandawa grew from 37 to 41 while that in nearby
Razhena village went up to 22 from 14.
</P>
<P>
An additional eight cases from a single family was reported
from Nauwasta village, the newspaper added.
</P>
<P>
A doctor was quoted as saying that the victims showed weakness
and loss of sensation in the lower limbs, and they were afflicted
with a form of neuritis.
</P>
<P>
A patient said he first suffered from body pain and then his
stomach started swelling. He soon lost appetite and had swollen
hands and legs. Finally he could not move any longer.
</P>
<P>
A medical team had been sent to the affected villages, but no
definite cause has been identified.
</P>
<P>
Doctors suspected that the victims had taken contaminated food,
the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
