<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khieu Samphan, Nuon Chea Defect to Cambodian Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Khieu Samphan and Nuon
Chea, the remaining Khmer Rouge hard-line leaders, defected to the
Royal Government of Cambodia Friday evening in Pailin, the Bayon
Radio reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two said they respected and highly praised the role played
by King Norodom Sihanouk. They also pledged they will recognize
Cambodia's Constitutions and the Royal Government, and said they
wish to return to the society as a civilian.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cambodia's Prime Minister Hun Sen has contacted with
Khieu Samphan through telephone to welcome their defection.
</P>
<P>
Khmer Rouge military leader Ta Mok, political leader Khieu
Samphan and former party number two Nuon Chea are the three
hard-line leaders remaining following the death of Pol Pot in
April. They were also left isolated by the disintegration of the
movement.
</P>
<P>
The last of Ta Mok's dwindling guerrilla army announced a
defection deal with the government on December 4.
</P>
<P>
Pailin officials said Khieu Samphan is well known in the former
rebel strongholds of Malai and Pailin and that he has many close
friends in Pailin, which is host to other Khmer Rouge
intellectuals and leaders, including former Khmer Rouge deputy
premier Ieng Sary.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that before their defection, the two had sent
letters separately to Prime Minister Hun Sen expressing their
wishes to return to the Royal Government.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen expressed his welcome after he got the support of King
Sihanouk who is in Beijing for a routine health checkup.
</P>
<P>
In his letter afterwards to Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, Hun
Sen highly praised their deeds. He said their defection will
greatly enhance the peace, reconciliation and the unity of the
nation and the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
