<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Officials Try to Save National on Death Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Foreign Ministry has
been trying to save a Thai national on death row in California,
claiming the legal process was undue and calling for clemency.
</P>
<P>
A foreign ministry official on Saturday confirmed newspaper
reports that Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan personally got
involved in the effort, having written to incoming California
governor Gray Davis asking him to review the sentence.
</P>
<P>
Jaturun Siripongs, 43, was convicted of killing his boss, the
owner of a neighborhood Thai market where he worked on weekends,
and a market worker. He was sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
A judge earlier this month rescheduled the execution for
February 9, putting the question of possible clemency before Davis
who is due to take office in January.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing governor Pete Wilso rejected an initial clemency plea
in November, but hours before the execution was scheduled to take
place a federal judge issued a temporary stay.
</P>
<P>
Surin said in the letter that the legal process had yet to be
completed, according to the official who refused to be named.
</P>
<P>
Surin would also make a telephone call to his U.S. counterpart,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, asking for clemency.
</P>
<P>
Surin's letter also alleged that Thai diplomats were denied
consular access to Jaturun before and during his trial.
</P>
<P>
Jaturun had acknowledged that he was present during the crime
in the town of Garden Grove southeast of Los Angeles but has said
that an accomplice committed the murders.
</P>
<P>
He has refused to name the accomplice, saying he feared
retaliation against his family.
</P>
<P>
Among those pleading for him is Surachia Wattanaporn, the
husband of one of the victims, a prison guard, and two members of
the jury that originally sentenced him to die. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
