<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slump Leads to Better Air Quality Over Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Air quality over Bangkok has
become cleaner because of the economic slump which has led to
fewer dust particles and less fume emissions, Thai
environmentalists said.
</P>
<P>
Reduced construction activity has cut the amount of dust in the
air which is below standard in residential areas, the Pollution
Control Department said in a statement, made public on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Automobile emissions, although they remain twice as high as the
acceptable standard, have improved considerably since the
financial crisis began last year, compared with two years ago when
the emissions were seven times higher, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Because of the slump, many people went to work by bus instead
of driving cars, thus reducing the number of cars on the streets,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
However, Bangkok residents are still at risk from increasing
ozone in the atmosphere in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Although the ozone layer in the stratosphere protects the earth
from dangerous ultraviolet radiation, ozone in the lower
atmosphere poses a health hazard.
</P>
<P>
Ozone content in the atmosphere above Bangkok has been measured
at between 0.25 and 0.28 milligram per cubic meter of air compared
to the acceptable standard of 0.2 mg/cubic meter, according to the
department.
</P>
<P>
The situation deteriorates in summer, particularly in the
northern part of Bangkok which is downwind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
