<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Khmer Rouge Leaders Khieu Samphan, Nuon Chea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 26 -- Khmer Rouge top leaders Khieu
Samphan and Nuon Chea have surrendered to the government, leaving
Cambodia's guerrilla force with its only military chief Ta Mok,
local radio reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Khieu Samphan, born in Svay Rieng province in 1934, studied at
Paris University and returned to Cambodia in 1956, where he
founded French-language journal "Observer".
</P>
<P>
After serving as Secretary of State for Commerce, Minister of
Economy and Minister of Commerce in the early 1960s, he left
Phnom Penh to join the Khmer Rouge in 1967.
</P>
<P>
He was Minister of Defense and Deputy Prime Minister in
1970-1976, elected politburo member of the National United Front
of Cambodia 1970-1975, and was Commander-in-Chief of the
Cambodian People's National Liberation Armed Forces in 1973-1975.
</P>
<P>
He became president of the state presidium in 1976 and was
prime minister in 1979 when the Khmer Rouge government was
toppled. He was in charge of foreign affairs in the Khmer Rouge
provisional government-in-exile during the 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Nuon Chea, born in Battambang province in 1927, studied at
Thammasat University in Bangkok, Thailand, in the 1940s and
returned to Cambodia in 1949.
</P>
<P>
He was Vice President of the Khmer Rouge military command and
political chief of the military in 1970-1975. He was president
of the parliament from 1976 to 1979 when the Khmer Rouge regime
was overthrown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
