<DOCNO> XIE19981226.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Production of Energy Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 26 (Xinhua) -- China's production of energy
dropped in the January-October period this year, according to the
latest figures released by the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Total energy production in the first ten months amounted to 938
million tons of standard coal equivalent, down 4.4 percent against
that of the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Production of coal dropped by 6.3 percent to 918.6 million
tons, that of crude oil decreased by 1.2 percent to 133.3 million
tons and that of natural gas dropped by 2.0 percent to 17.8
billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the output of electricity increased by 2.3 percent
to 923.2 billion kwh. The output of thermal power amounted to 744
billion kwh, up 1.3 percent, that of hydro-electric power 166
billion kwh, up 6.0 percent, and that of nuclear power 12.7
billion kwh, up 5.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
