<DOCNO> XIE19981226.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Adopts Fiscal 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government
approved Friday a record 81.86 trillion yen (about 705.7 billion
U.S. dollars) national budget for fiscal 1999, which starts next
April 1.
</P>
<P>
The budget, 5.4 percent larger than the initial budget for
fiscal 1998, is aimed at lifting the Japanese economy out of its
longest and deepest recession since the end of World War II,
observers said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa hailed the budget as the best
possible way to achieve the government's forecast of 0.5 percent
economic growth for fiscal 1999 -- the first positive growth in
three years.
</P>
<P>
Spending on public works projects provided for in the proposed
budget plan is up by 5 percent to 9,430.0 billion yen (81.3
billion dollars) over the initial budget for the current fiscal
year, ending next March 31.
</P>
<P>
Another key pillar of the budget plan, now pending the
approval of the Diet, or the Japanese parliament, when it meets
on January 19 next year, is a record 9.4 trillion yen (81 billion
dollars) worth of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
To finance the budget, the government will have to float a
record 31.05 trillion yen (267.7 billion dollars) in new bonds,
bringing the balance of outstanding bonds to some 327 trillion
yen (2,818.9 billion dollars) at the end of March 2000.
</P>
<P>
The defense budget was cut for the second straight years to
4,932.2 billion yen (42.5 billion dollars), down 0.2 percent.
Japan's defense spending was curtailed for the first time in
fiscal 1998 since the Defense Agency was set up in 1954.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Official Development Assistance (ODA), which was cut
for the first time in fiscal 1998, rises by 0.2 percent to
1,048.9 billion yen (9.0 billion dollars) in the new budget.
</P>
<P>
The ODA budget includes 20 billion yen (172 million dollars)
for a fund within the Asian Development Bank to help
crisis-stricken Asian countries raise funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
