<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Price Index Rises 9.2 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's consumer price index
of 1998 increased by 9.2 percent over last year's figure, Vietnam
News Agency (VNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Foodgrain and foodstuff registered the highest yearly price
rise at 23.1 and 8.6 percent, followed by education, 9.6 percent,
and pharmaceuticals and medical service, 8.7 percent, VNA quoted
Vietnam's General Department of Statistics as saying.
</P>
<P>
The prices of drinks, cigarettes, garments, headgear, footwear,
transportation and post service cost rose between 2.3-5.3 percent
for the year, and a mere 0.3 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
The costs of construction materials and household appliances
rose slightly through the year, with 1.7 and 3.2 percent over that
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold rose only 0.7 percent. And compared with last
month, the gold price dropped 0.1 percent in Hanoi and 0.3 percent
in Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the exchange rate for the U.S. dollar
increased by 9.6 percent compared with last year, but fell 0.4
percent compared with November.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's market experts predict that the price for foodgrain
will continue to rise next month due to the Vietnamese
government's measures to adjust the paddy rice price in order to
stimulate purchasing power in rural areas. The price for
industrial consumer goods is also expected to rise due to the
upcoming Lunar New Year, which falls on February 16, but at a
modest level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
