<HEADLINE> Peru Reports Significant Antidrug Achievement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Peruvian authorities Friday
reported significant achievement in the nation's fight against
drugs in the outgoing year, as official statistics showed the
country no longer the biggest coca producer in the world.
</P>
<P>
A total of 13,719 people were arrested in police antidrug
operations in 1998, with 2,797 charged with illicit drug
trafficking and 10,922 with drug consumption. Police seized 35
tons of drugs and destroyed 11 underground factories.
</P>
<P>
Coca leaf cultivation has been reduced by 5,152 hectares from
69,000 hectares in 1997, as many coca cultivators turned to other
profitable crops under the government's 1998-2000 National Plan
of War Against Drugs.
</P>
<P>
The plan aims to cut the country's coca cultivation by half in
the next five years and to eliminate it all in 10 years. 
</P>
