<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Chinese PR Companies Grow Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 26 (Xinhua) -- A survey shows that domestic
public relations (PR) companies in major cities are growing faster
than overseas-funded ones in China, China Daily reports today.
</P>
<P>
The growth of the local PR industry is indicated in the
increase of the number of employees. Nine firms surveyed by the
Chinese International Public Relations Association (CIPRA) in
major cities, like Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, had more than
30 employees each.
</P>
<P>
Annual sales of the surveyed domestic PR companies reached or
approached 20 million yuan (2.4 million U.S. dollars), with
annual growth rates of more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the local companies are no match for their
overseas-funded counterparts, said Professor Guo Huimin, deputy
general secretary of CIPRA.
</P>
<P>
"The major services now provided by some local PR companies are
what foreign-invested companies did years ago," Guo was quoted by
the paper as saying. They lack experience and "are doing more
communication work like publicity for their clients instead of
offering consulting services."
</P>
<P>
Guo called for more cooperation between domestic and
overseas-funded PR companies. He said: "The two sides can
complement each other in business."
</P>
<P>
Guo pinpointed four major problems for China's present PR
market: frequent outflow of experienced personnel, imperfect
market regulations, inconsistent service quality and insufficient
awareness of the PR needs from domestic enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
