<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Tighten Control on Quake Forecasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 26 (Xinhua) -- China will keep a closer rein
on earthquake forecast information to forestall false alarms set
off by rumors, today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
"All work units and individuals should not release their
earthquake forecast results to society or abroad without the
permission of the State," the paper quoted a regulation endorsed
by Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji on December 17 as saying.
</P>
<P>
Quake forecasts and related reports should only be released by
the State. Nationwide earthquakes predicted to strike in up to 10
years are to be announced by the State Council, according to the
regulation.
</P>
<P>
Provincial governments are responsible for quake forecasts in
their localities.
</P>
<P>
Individuals should report immediately to governments when they
observe abnormal natural phenomenon which may indicate potential
earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
Quake forecasts should highlight their scientific nature and
the potential effects on the social and economic life.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also requires media to abide by the regulation
when news about earthquake forecasts is released.
</P>
<P>
China announced this week, that ti will spend 2.5 billion yuan
over the next five years on basic research programs, including the
application of the forecasting of strong earthquakes and other
natural disasters, according to the paper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
