<HEADLINE> Tokyo's Historical Perception Unchanged, Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government's
historical perception remains unchanged despite a recent court
ruling involving the 1937 Nanjing Massacre committed by the
Japanese army, Foreign Ministry spokesman Sadaaki Numata said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"It was a civil libel case not involving the government, and
the ruling had nothing to do with judging the historical facts of
the Nanjing incident," Numata said.
</P>
<P>
"Our historical perception remains unchanged ... about the
fact the massacre of civilians (in the Chinese city of Nanjing)
occurred," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Tokyo High Court rejected World War II
Japanese soldier Shiro Azuma's appeal challenging a district
court ruling on his personal diary.
</P>
<P>
Azuma, 86, witnessed and kept a diary on the hair-raising
killings of Chinese servicemen and civilians by the Japanese army
in the attack on Nanjing in 1937.
</P>
<P>
Azuma published the personal diary in which he recorded the
atrocities committed by Japanese soldiers and mentioned by name
some of those who perpetrated the bloody deeds.
</P>
<P>
In the spring of 1993, Koji Hashimoto, one of the soldiers
mentioned in the diary, sued Azuma for "damaging his reputation."
</P>
<P>
On April 26, 1994, the Tokyo District Court ruled that the
Azuma diary "was judged as being unnatural by common sense" and
that Azuma pay the plaintiff 500,000 yen (about 4,310 U.S.
dollars) in "compensation for damage to his reputation."
</P>
<P>
Azuma then appealed to the High Court of Tokyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
